# DRY: extract helpers and avoid duplication

Eliminate duplication. One source of truth per concept. **Extract helpers even when small** — if the same logic or value appears in more than one place, pull it out.

## Repeated code → extract a helper

- **Second occurrence:** If you are about to copy a few lines (or the same condition + block) to another branch or function, extract a small helper or shared function instead.
- **Same validation in multiple places:** One function, called from all call sites.
- **Near-identical blocks:** Parameterize the difference and use a single function.

```cpp
// ❌ Duplicated
if (index >= 0 && index < static_cast<int>(list.size()) && list[index].active) { ... }
// ... later ...
if (index >= 0 && index < static_cast<int>(list.size()) && list[index].active) { ... }

// ✅ Single helper
static bool IsValidEntry(const List& list, int index) { ... }
if (IsValidEntry(list, index)) { ... }
```

## Repeated values → one constant

- **Same literal in two places:** Define a named constant (file or namespace scope) and use it everywhere. Search the repo first; if the value or concept already exists, reuse it.
- **Shared constants:** Use project locations (e.g. `settings_defaults` in `core/Settings.h`, `file_time_constants` in `utils/FileTimeTypes.h`) for app-wide values; one constant per purpose.

```cpp
// ❌ Same meaning, two literals
if (interval < 1) interval = 1;
if (interval > 60) interval = 60;
// ... elsewhere ...
if (val < 1) val = 1;
if (val > 60) val = 60;

// ✅ One constant (or reuse from settings_defaults)
constexpr int kMinRecrawlMinutes = 1, kMaxRecrawlMinutes = 60;
```

## Also avoid

- Duplicated string literals (labels, errors, tooltips): centralize or use one constant.
- Duplicated documentation: one canonical place and reference it.
- Second type alias for the same type: use the existing alias.

